General FAQ

This document is a community driven full breakdown of the respective class. This is a live document where we actively change it based on feedback and changes to the game to provide the best information to the community. The majority of us hang around in the Community Lost Ark Discord in our respective class channels. If you would like to give us feedback or ask questions contact us there.

Why should I play this class?

The Glaivier class is a durable, well-rounded and standout flavor of the Martial Artist classes, wielding a Glaive and Spear with stylistic, ferocious but elegant flair and handle extremely well at multiple ranges. Their Class Engravings, Pinnacle and Control, offer a burst-like DPS style or consistent uptime. They are exceptional at rounding out nearly any composition with their strong access to stagger and weak point utilities.

Class Identity

Weapon Stances

The Glaivier class utilizes two weapons, the Glaive and the Spear, each with their unique set of skills in their respective Flurry Stance and Focus Stance, also commonly referred to as Blue and Red.

Using the <Z> key will swap you between these two stances.

In KR translations, you may see Flurry referred to as Rampage, and Focus as Concentration.

The blocks on the bottom of the Identity interface indicate the cooldown status of skills in the opposing stance (with respect to their hotkey position).

Colored blocks indicate the skill is off cooldown (ready to use). Non-colored, or gray, blocks indicate the skill is still on cooldown (not ready to use).

Two hotkeys are naturally unassigned by default in Focus Stance.

Dual Meter

The Glaivier's functional Class Identity is the Dual Meter, a three-part gauge.

The Dual Meter is primarily filled through landing abilities and also generates slowly over time. Basic attacks are also able to generate small amounts of meter.

Swapping stances will consume 1 bar of meter and grant a buff respective to the active stance. If you have less than 1 bar of meter, you do not gain anything.

Flurry

Unless you have the Pinnacle class engraving equipped, the stance buffs are mutually exclusive, meaning your current stance buff will be replaced by the other stance buff when you change stances. If you have less than 1 bar of meter and swap, you will also lose your current buff.

How do I decide on a build?

Both have their strengths and weaknesses. It’s a matter of personal preference.

Here’s a short summary of the builds. For further information, read their respective sections of this document.

What are my Party Synergies?

Synergies are buffs or applied debuffs that your party can benefit from. These only apply to those in your party and not the entire raid. Consistent synergies generally have high uptime during the fight while Burst synergies are more infrequent.

What are the key pieces of my build?

 Pinnacle

 Control

Runes

Runes are not a particular necessity on most Pinnacle builds, however they do offer some level of benefit, with Galewind runes in particular being desirable for accelerating slower skills.

Due to mana issues Control requires access to Focus, Conviction and Judgment runes to mitigate this. Galewind runes are also important for reducing the length of their skill animations.

Skill Points

As Pinnacle has their skills spread across two different stances, they have a lot of access to various utility skills, but it also means that investing into them with a low amount of Skill Points is difficult.

With only one stance to deal with, Control builds do not struggle in particular with Skill Point investment but some skills will play significantly differently at low point investments.

Gems

Pinnacle has a few standout damage skills that greatly benefit from having high level Damage Gems compared to others. They also require four identical level Cooldown Gems for consistency.

As many of Control’s skills deal roughly around the same damage, having high level gems do not impact the build as significantly.

Why is Yearning important?

Yearning is a Relic set that is usually equipped by Supports and grants +8/10/12% Damage and Attack/Move Speed to the party within a radius, represented by a ring around them. Due to its ubiquitous presence, the Yearning set’s buffs are considered to be a commonplace part of any build despite being from an external source.

Written by Kaeox

Playstyle

The Pinnacle Class Engraving combines the two opposing buffs the Glaivier ordinarily receives from their Class Identity, the Dual Meter, when swapping stances. This grants the class a simultaneous buff to their damage, crit damage, attack speed and move speed in both stances, greatly amplifying damage output and streamlining their gameplay fluidity.

This engraving retains the original Glaivier gameplay loop of stance swapping, continuously cycling through the rampaging skills of Flurry Stance (Blue) and channeling the high-impact skills in Focus Stance (Red), the latter of which also scales additionally through the Specialization stat to explosively increase their damage.

Compared to their pre-rework state, Pinnacle has transitioned from non-positional consistent DPS to concentrated burst-like Entropy DPS, trading mostly stagger output for a higher, but more difficult to achieve, damage ceiling. They however still remain exceptional at situational adaptation, retaining their wide array of flexible tripods and utility skills, being especially reliable in progressive or even equalized environments like Inferno Mode.

Stat Allocation

Specialization (Spec) is Pinnacle’s main stat as it greatly increases their Focus skill damage and Dual Meter gain, in addition to the default Awakening damage increase.

Crit is the recommended substat for maintaining damage consistency regardless of composition or situation.

Swiftness (Swift) is a substat option that is best in optimized environments and does not always translate to a direct DPS increase due to the variable benefit of cooldown reduction.

Notes

  • Spec/Crit is the default recommendation, and is the most consistent build.
  • For Entropy builds, your Bracelet sub-stat priority can be ignored if it has at least 200 total stat (Spec-favored), with 2 acceptable damage lines (i.e. Fervor & Precise).
  • Nightmare builds do not derive a high amount of value from Spec Crit bracelets.

Gear Set

The recommended Pinnacle Relic set is Entropy.

Entropy is a powerful Relic set that allows Pinnacle builds to achieve more reliable Crit rate while capitalizing on the compounding damage bonuses from back attacking to scale extremely high numbers. Since the Akkan-patch, due to reworks to Glaivier’s Class Identity granting attack speed in both weapon stances and tripods changes, Entropy is no longer considered unrealistic DPS due to being too slow for reliable execution.

Nightmare builds, the former meta, are still considered playable with some adjustments, however note the damage gap between Nightmare and Entropy builds can be as high as a 20% difference. Due to inevitable downtime introduced between major skill rotations, mana management is no longer considered a critical impediment (excluding needlessly spamming filler skills). As such the Salvation set is also no longer considered a viable sidegrade as the damage trade off for attack speed is no longer considered worthwhile.

Remember, with Relic Conversion you are able to freely swap between Relic sets.

Engravings

Here are the Engravings you should aim to use,

and why you would choose specific combinations of Engravings to make a build.

Mandatory

Pinnacle

When swapping stances, additionally gain 40/60/100% of the opposing stance buff.

  • Flurry Stance: 15% Attack Speed, 20% Damage (20s)
  • Focus Stance: 15% Move Speed, 60% Crit Damage (15s)
  • Swapping stances always replaces your current buff. if you swap without sufficient meter, you will gain no buff.
  • Stance buffs are static values meaning Level 1 and 2 are sharp drops in efficiency compared to Level 3.

  • Cursed Doll 3 vs. Adrenaline 3
  • Adrenaline: This is based on how well you can keep up Adrenaline, which isn’t difficult in a rotation. However Glaivier doesn’t ramp up Adrenaline to 6 stacks very well, so situations where cutscenes or mechanics forcibly time you out makes this a high liability, especially like Shock Training Scrapper for instance, it relies on the Crit Chance to make the engraving worthwhile.
  • Cursed Doll: Stop tanking with your face, use better potions, and scream Medic! at your support to scream at you to stop getting hit. You have permanent engraving uptime for a permanent downside, fair is fair.

  • Spec/Swift Necklace, Crit Bracelet
  • This build is calculated when both Adrenaline and Ether Predator are at FULL STACKS, operating at 100% UPTIME. This has the highest theoretical DPS but the margin gained is minimal compared to the options below.
  • Swift Necklace adds to Raid Captain efficiency, and minimizes Crit synergy inefficiencies.
  • Option 2: Spec/Swift/Crit - Cursed Doll 3, Adrenaline 1
  • Spec/Swift Neck, Crit Ring, Crit Bracelet
  • This is the best build in optimal situations (i.e. the boss is standing still for a long time, Trixion). It requires a Crit synergy to reap the full benefits of the build but is strong regardless. Note that the theoretical value is contentious because the return value on Swiftness stat (the cooldown reduction) can be extremely variable depending on uptime. Probably the cheapest variation FWIW because good Spec accessories are always contested.
  • Swift Necklace adds to Raid Captain efficiency, and minimizes Crit synergy inefficiencies.
  • Option 3: Spec/Crit - Cursed Doll 3, Adrenaline 1
  • Spec/Crit Necklace, Crit Bracelet
  • This is the most CONSISTENT build, that will perform with or without good teammates. I recommend this to most players. Although it means your overall DPS may be lower over time (esp. with Crit synergy overflow), it opens up party slots for damage synergy (i.e. Deathblade, Gunlancer). It is also fairly strong in the burst-favored raid meta in the game as you’re far less likely to whiff a white number on big skills which, let’s face it, feels really f***ing bad.

Rotations

Entropy

Make sure you have enough meter to swap for stance buff. Use filler skills, or RDS, to fill.

Only use Awakening if you have your stance buff active. You can also wait until your Support has full-buffed before using if timing it to the Boss phase is not important.

Nightmare

Nightmare 0 Meter

If you play Nightmare, congratulations, your opener is annoying. This is actually so annoying to deal with that I’m not going to even edit this (for now).

As you’re forced to use Awakening in your opener for Nightmare you obviously also want it to maximize its damage with buffs where possible. However, if you opt to use Final Decision on HMS, how much meter (and what stance) you start in is annoyingly important.

If you have 1.5>x<2 bars in Red, or 2.5>x<3 bars in Blue (same thing), Shackle > HMS will always consume a bar for Final Decision and leave you without enough meter to swap.

With <x.5 bars, naturally HMS will not get buffed by Final Decision There are 2 possible solutions to remove this problem entirely:

  • Take Vital Point Hit on HMS and whatever you do, it doesn't matter at the cost of a minor~medium DPS loss (depending on Crit synergies).
  • Or you skip HMS entirely for the opening rotation until your next Shackling (very simple).

Alternate solutions to keep using HMS with Final Decision are:

  • Tell Nightmare players to actively keep track of their stance & meter, and use filler skills to move themselves out of the danger zone, slightly delaying their DPS.

Stagger

Use remaining filler whenever.

FAQ: Pinnacle

Questions sourced from frequent interactions within the Unofficial Lost Ark Discord

What should I do if I don’t like Grudge?

Why is SBD Quick Prep at Lv.1 and not Lv.5?

Cooldown of Shackling Blue Dragon

30s (base CD) - 6s (Quick Prep 1) - Y% (Lv.X CD Gem) = 24s - Y%

Cooldown of RDH, Thrust, & SFP

 24s (base CD) - Y% (Lv.X CD Gem) = 24s - Y%

This means the CDs of all four skills align perfectly and allows you to seamlessly chain the four skills together without worry. Otherwise, it would require you to either track the CD or check the icon CD on the Identity, both of which can result in overlapping CDs due to margins of error, delaying your Focus skill rotation and therefore pushing back your DPS. Once or twice is not much of a change, but the accumulative loss can be significant.

But we still have Tripod slots, can I still use SBD Quick Prep 5?

You will always have remaining Tripods that you can’t use unless you tweak your build for certain utilities. There is only one way that Shackling Quick Prep 5 has recommended viability and that’s when you already have Lv.10 CD gems on RDH, Thrust, & SFP and not on Shackling.

Cooldown of Shackling Blue Dragon

30s (base CD) - 11s (Quick Prep 5) = 19s

Cooldown of RDH, Thrust, & SFP

 24s (base CD) - 20% (Lv.10 CD Gem) = 19.2s

It is possible, but not recommended to use CD Gems lower than Lv.10 as each level pushes the gap between Shackling and Focus skills a bit further.

Should I use Precise Slash on RDS?

You see that? That’s right, that juicy Precise Slash tripod on Raging Dragon Slash, sitting there enticing you with those sensuously big numbers, just waiting to be used.

120% vs. 70%? GYAAT DAMN. IT’S FREE DAMA—

 Oh.

Yeah that’s basically it. Galewind barely puts a dent into that cast time. Long and short, Precise Slash makes RDS do really big damage (but hardly compares to Focus skills) but it makes it significantly harder to land unless you really know the ins-and-outs of the raid, and you also lose about 20% stagger on the skill. It’s pretty much a DPS gremlin tripod because you drop a lot to gain a bit more damage.

Why is Adrenaline 3 considered bad?

Because you overcap on Crit rate, and to avoid overcapping on Crit rate, you drop Spec to balance damage gained from Swift through Raid Captain. This also assumes you never drop the buff, and once you do you don’t have an engraving for a few seconds.

Is Pinnacle’s buff considered Additional Damage?

No, while the buff shows up under Additional Damage stat in the Character Profile, mathematically it is applied as a multiplicative buff.

Control

Moderation/Temperance [KR] | Full Moon [RU]

Written by Kaeox

Playstyle

The Control Class Engraving simplifies the Glaivier playstyle, forgoing and disabling the use of the Focus Stance and stance swapping in exchange for a flat damage increase to all Flurry Stance skills. As a tradeoff, its DPS is scaled through constant uptime that is heavily reliant upon back attacking, using Ambush Master and the Entropy Relic set in order to raise its DPS. As a Swiftness stacking class, you have naturally high movement speed and low cooldowns which aid in maneuvering around in raids.

Stat Allocation

Swiftness (Swift) is Control’s main stat as the class’ primary method of scaling DPS is through using the attack speed and cooldown reduction to relentlessly spam skills with back attack modifiers. The movement speed scales Raid Captain and aids nimble movement.

Crit substat allows for better crit rate and damage consistency.

Gear Set

The recommended Control Relic set is Entropy.

Entropy is the most powerful Relic set for Control as it has multiple useful stats in one package, and all of the class’ damage numbers are scaled through compounding back damage modifiers.

2-set Nightmare is useful in non-competitive environments to stall mana drain but results in a significant damage drop. 4-set+ Nightmare builds are not recommended because it exposes too many weaknesses, and Boundless Mana does not outcompete the loss of Magick Addiction’s damage modifiers.

Remember, with Relic Conversion you are able to freely swap between Relic sets.

FAQ: Control

Questions sourced from frequent interactions within the Unofficial Lost Ark Discord

What should I do if I don’t like Grudge?

“I’m out of mana!”

You’re going to go OOM at some point, this is inevitable. The few ways you can mitigate this is eating food like Masterwork Herb Steak (a.k.a. the mana gold tax) for increased mana regeneration. In the case of Supports, Bard is preferred over Artist, where Paladin is the least optimal for mana regen. Summoner also has a synergy that increases mana regen.

The MP Recovery line on Bracelets is extremely strong for mana drain mitigation due to the amount of skills that are used.

The final solution is to use the Focus Rune build.

The cursed solution is 2-set Nightmare.

Should I go Cursed Doll or Adrenaline?

Cursed Doll is permanent and consistent. Other than the reduced healing, there are no real problems with it… unless you get hit a lot, but that’s a different issue now.

Adrenaline has a very slightly higher ceiling, but requires you maintain your stacks as much as possible or your damage will suffer. While better than most classes that can’t spam skills, failing to maintain Adrenaline stacks a few times will easily make it worse than Cursed Doll.

For Adrenaline management outside DPS periods, one option is Thorn Jab with or without Quick Prep, enabling a permanent uptime. This option comes at the cost of the Excellent Mobility tripod on Thorn Jab which some people prefer and/or rely on, but with practice, can easily be overcome. This is your preference.

Can I build more Crit?

22% (Entropy) + 23% (643+ Crit) + 20% (Shackling Blue Dragon) + 10% (Back Attack) + 5% (Adrenaline) = 80% Crit rate.

No, you really don’t need it.

Is there a non-back attack build?

Yes, and it’s exceedingly dogs***. It uses Nightmare, and Keen Blunt Weapon over Ambush Master. For your information, there is no situation where Boundless Mana can outpace the loss of Magick Addiction because you become animation capped. You will become literally incapable of dealing damage any faster. Why isn’t it in the guide? It is, it’s right here at the bottom of the barrel.
